{"title_page": "The Room Tribute", "text_new": "{{short description|2010 flash video game}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title      = The Room Tribute\n|image      = Theroomgame.jpg\n|caption    = The game mocks the movie's dialogue, such as its overuse of the greeting \"Oh hi\".\n|developer  = [[Newgrounds]]\n|publisher  = Newgrounds\n|series     = \n|artist     = Jeff Bandelin\n|composer   = Chris O'Neill\n|programmer = Tom Fulp\n|engine     = [[Adobe Flash]]\n|released   = September 3, 2010\n|genre      = [[Point-and-click adventure game]]\n|modes      = [[Single-player]]\n|platforms  = [[Web browser]]\n}}\n'''''The Room Tribute''''' (also known as '''''The Room: The Game''''') is a [[point-and-click adventure game]] released on September 3, 2010, that serves as an unofficial adaptation of the 2003 film ''[[The Room (film)|The Room]]'' directed by [[Tommy Wiseau]]. It was programmed by [[Newgrounds]] founder Tom Fulp, with artwork by Newgrounds staff member Jeff \"JohnnyUtah\" Bandelin, and music by animator Chris O'Neill. The game was designed in the style of 16-bit graphics, much like similar games based on the films ''[[Tremors (film)|Tremors]]'' and ''[[The Hunger Games (film)|The Hunger Games]]'' for Newgrounds' own 2010 and 2012 [[April Fools' Day|April Fools]] jokes.\n\n==Gameplay==\n''The Room Tribute'' is a [[graphic adventure game]] with a [[point and click]] interface. The player assumes the role of Johnny, a banker in San Francisco, as he goes about his daily life \u2014 showering, going to work and pleasing his future wife Lisa. The game is divided up into several levels, each of which takes the form of a new day. Each level begins with Johnny being required to bathe and ends with him going to bed; in between, Johnny is tasked with various missions, which usually involve him engaging in mundane activities such as meeting friends for coffee, buying new clothes and playing catch. When not on a mission, the player is given free roam over a small area of San Francisco, which includes a park, several stores and the homes of Johnny's friends Mark and Denny. There are several [[side quest]]s that the player can engage in when not on missions, such as reading Denny's daily diary entries or finding ten hidden spoons, which unlocks an extended ending to the game.\n\n==Plot==\nFor the most part, the game follows the plot of the movie: amiable banker Johnny helps his friends with their day-to-day problems while preparing for his wedding to his future wife, Lisa. When he discovers that Lisa is cheating on him with his best friend Mark, Johnny is outraged and ultimately kills himself. The game diverges from the film by only showing the events from Johnny's point of view. The player controls Johnny as he engages in activities that were only referred to in the film, such as his taking on a mystery client at his bank and his turning over drug dealer Chris-R to the police. The game also contains several in-jokes that attempt to provide backstories and account for idiosyncrasies in the film and its story. For example, a scene in the game's final level attempts to explain the inexplicable disappearance of supporting character Peter from the final act by revealing that an escaped Chris-R, in an act of revenge for his arrest, stole Johnny's car during the party and killed Peter in a [[hit and run]].\n\nThe game begins with a prologue, showing Lisa and Denny at Johnny's grave (a statue of Tommy Wiseau) and then segueing into a level that occurs a day before the main action of the movie begins, in which Johnny learns that an earthquake has sealed San Francisco off from the rest of the state. The final level of the game permits players to \"tie up\" loose plot threads left hanging at the end of the film, such as the fate of Chris-R and Johnny's contentious relationship with his superiors at the bank. The game also includes an epilogue revealing that Johnny was, in fact, an alien being inhabiting a human body; after Johnny's \"suicide\", he returns to his [[mother ship]], a giant mechanical spoon orbiting the Earth, and laments how he and his fellow extraterrestrials may never understand human life. Johnny and two of his fellow aliens then assume forms resembling a naked Tommy Wiseau and begin dancing, ending the game.\n\nShould the player collect each of the hidden spoons throughout the game, rather than simply dance during the climax the aliens fire a ray gun at Earth that reshapes the planet into a giant spoon.\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called the flash game \"as addictive as scotchka!\".<ref>{{cite web|title='The Room: The Game': Good Idea|url=https://ew.com/article/2010/09/06/the-room-video-game/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last1=Ward|first1=Kate|accessdate=September 8, 2010|date=September 6, 2010}}</ref> The game has also received positive reviews from [[Time (magazine)|''TIME'']],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2010/09/08/the-room-game-will-tear-you-apart-lisa/|title=The Room Game Will Tear You Apart, Lisa!|last1=Jones|first1=Nate|date=September 9, 2010|work=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> [[Wired (magazine)|''Wired'']],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/09/the-room-newgrounds/|last1=Mastrapa|first1=Gus|title=Cult Flick The Room Inspires Point-and-Click Adventure|date=September 7, 2010|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Destructoid]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.destructoid.com/oh-hai-the-room-tribute-you-are-my-favorite-flash-game--183329.phtml|title=Oh hai The Room tribute! You are my favorite Flash game!|date=September 7, 2010|work=[[Destructoid]]|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> [[Escapist Magazine|''The Escapist'']],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/103329-The-Room-Goes-From-Bad-Movie-to-Great-Game|last1=Thompson|first1=Mike|title=The Room Goes From Bad Movie to Great Game|date=September 8, 2010|work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> Bitmob,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Minotti|first1=Mike|title=Oh Hai, Bitmob! Play The Room Game!|url=http://bitmob.com/articles/oh-hai-bitmob-play-the-room-game|accessdate=October 9, 2017|work=Bitmob|date=September 9, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330022351/http://bitmob.com/articles/oh-hai-bitmob-play-the-room-game|archivedate=March 30, 2012}}</ref> Infinite Lives,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frank|first1=Jenn|url=https://infinitelives.net/2010/09/08/the-room-the-video-game/|title=The Room, the video game|date=September 8, 2010|work=Infinite Lives|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Westword]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Klosowski|first1=Thorin|url=https://www.westword.com/arts/browser-pick-of-the-week-the-room-tribute-nsfw-5783186|title=Browser Pick of the Week: The Room Tribute (NSFW)|date=September 8, 2010|work=[[Westword]]|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> Game Culture,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gameculture.com/2010/09/07/room-point-and-click-8-bit-adventure-game|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100912145224/http://www.gameculture.com/2010/09/07/room-point-and-click-8-bit-adventure-game|archivedate=2010-09-12|title=The Room as a Point and Click, 8-Bit Adventure Game|date=September 9, 2010|work=Game Culture|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> and Geeks of Doom.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dussault|first1=Jason|url=https://geeksofdoom.com/2010/09/09/must-play-tribute-flash-game-based-on-tommy-wiseaus-the-room/|title=Must Play: Tribute Flash Game Based On Tommy Wiseau\u2019s \u2018The Room\u2019|date=September 9, 2010|work=Geeks of Doom|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn co-star [[Greg Sestero]]'s memoir, ''[[The Disaster Artist]]'', Sestero stated that during the filming of ''The Room'', he came up with the idea of having Mark be an undercover narcotics police officer to account for the disparate elements of his character, but the idea was rejected by Wiseau. Sestero \"had a good laugh\" when playing the game and seeing that its developers had given Mark a similar backstory by portraying him as a narcissistic [[hedonist]].<ref name=\"disaster\">''The Disaster Artist: My Life Inside the Room'' by [[Greg Sestero]] and [[Tom Bissell]], pg. 196. [[Simon & Schuster]], 2013.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.newgrounds.com/portal/view/547307}}\n*{{imdbtitle|7386506|The Room Tribute}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Room Tribute, The}}\n[[Category:2010 video games]]\n[[Category:Browser games]]\n[[Category:Fangames]]\n[[Category:Flash games]]\n[[Category:Role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Video games based on films]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 2003]]\n[[Category:Video games set in San Francisco]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title      = The Room Tribute\n|image      = Theroomgame.jpg\n|caption    = The game mocks the movie's dialogue, such as its overuse of the greeting \"Oh hi\".\n|developer  = [[Newgrounds]]\n|publisher  = Newgrounds\n|series     = \n|artist     = Jeff Bandelin\n|composer   = Chris O'Neill\n|programmer = Tom Fulp\n|engine     = [[Adobe Flash]]\n|released   = September 3, 2010\n|genre      = [[Point-and-click adventure game]]\n|modes      = [[Single-player]]\n|platforms  = [[Web browser]]\n}}\n'''''The Room Tribute''''' (also known as '''''The Room: The Game''''') is a [[point-and-click adventure game]] released on September 3, 2010, that serves as an unofficial adaptation of the 2003 film ''[[The Room (film)|The Room]]'' directed by [[Tommy Wiseau]]. It was programmed by [[Newgrounds]] founder Tom Fulp, with artwork by Newgrounds staff member Jeff \"JohnnyUtah\" Bandelin, and music by animator Chris O'Neill. The game was designed in the style of 16-bit graphics, much like similar games based on the films ''[[Tremors (film)|Tremors]]'' and ''[[The Hunger Games (film)|The Hunger Games]]'' for Newgrounds' own 2010 and 2012 [[April Fools' Day|April Fools]] jokes.\n\n==Gameplay==\n''The Room Tribute'' is a [[graphic adventure game]] with a [[point and click]] interface. The player assumes the role of Johnny, a banker in San Francisco, as he goes about his daily life \u2014 showering, going to work and pleasing his future wife Lisa. The game is divided up into several levels, each of which takes the form of a new day. Each level begins with Johnny being required to bathe and ends with him going to bed; in between, Johnny is tasked with various missions, which usually involve him engaging in mundane activities such as meeting friends for coffee, buying new clothes and playing catch. When not on a mission, the player is given free roam over a small area of San Francisco, which includes a park, several stores and the homes of Johnny's friends Mark and Denny. There are several [[side quest]]s that the player can engage in when not on missions, such as reading Denny's daily diary entries or finding ten hidden spoons, which unlocks an extended ending to the game.\n\n==Plot==\nFor the most part, the game follows the plot of the movie: amiable banker Johnny helps his friends with their day-to-day problems while preparing for his wedding to his future wife, Lisa. When he discovers that Lisa is cheating on him with his best friend Mark, Johnny is outraged and ultimately kills himself. The game diverges from the film by only showing the events from Johnny's point of view. The player controls Johnny as he engages in activities that were only referred to in the film, such as his taking on a mystery client at his bank and his turning over drug dealer Chris-R to the police. The game also contains several in-jokes that attempt to provide backstories and account for idiosyncrasies in the film and its story. For example, a scene in the game's final level attempts to explain the inexplicable disappearance of supporting character Peter from the final act by revealing that an escaped Chris-R, in an act of revenge for his arrest, stole Johnny's car during the party and killed Peter in a [[hit and run]].\n\nThe game begins with a prologue, showing Lisa and Denny at Johnny's grave (a statue of Tommy Wiseau) and then segueing into a level that occurs a day before the main action of the movie begins, in which Johnny learns that an earthquake has sealed San Francisco off from the rest of the state. The final level of the game permits players to \"tie up\" loose plot threads left hanging at the end of the film, such as the fate of Chris-R and Johnny's contentious relationship with his superiors at the bank. The game also includes an epilogue revealing that Johnny was, in fact, an alien being inhabiting a human body; after Johnny's \"suicide\", he returns to his [[mother ship]], a giant mechanical spoon orbiting the Earth, and laments how he and his fellow extraterrestrials may never understand human life. Johnny and two of his fellow aliens then assume forms resembling a naked Tommy Wiseau and begin dancing, ending the game.\n\nShould the player collect each of the hidden spoons throughout the game, rather than simply dance during the climax the aliens fire a ray gun at Earth that reshapes the planet into a giant spoon.\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called the flash game \"as addictive as scotchka!\".<ref>{{cite web|title='The Room: The Game': Good Idea|url=https://ew.com/article/2010/09/06/the-room-video-game/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last1=Ward|first1=Kate|accessdate=September 8, 2010|date=September 6, 2010}}</ref> The game has also received positive reviews from [[Time (magazine)|''TIME'']],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2010/09/08/the-room-game-will-tear-you-apart-lisa/|title=The Room Game Will Tear You Apart, Lisa!|last1=Jones|first1=Nate|date=September 9, 2010|work=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> [[Wired (magazine)|''Wired'']],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/09/the-room-newgrounds/|last1=Mastrapa|first1=Gus|title=Cult Flick The Room Inspires Point-and-Click Adventure|date=September 7, 2010|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Destructoid]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.destructoid.com/oh-hai-the-room-tribute-you-are-my-favorite-flash-game--183329.phtml|title=Oh hai The Room tribute! You are my favorite Flash game!|date=September 7, 2010|work=[[Destructoid]]|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> [[Escapist Magazine|''The Escapist'']],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/103329-The-Room-Goes-From-Bad-Movie-to-Great-Game|last1=Thompson|first1=Mike|title=The Room Goes From Bad Movie to Great Game|date=September 8, 2010|work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> Bitmob,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Minotti|first1=Mike|title=Oh Hai, Bitmob! Play The Room Game!|url=http://bitmob.com/articles/oh-hai-bitmob-play-the-room-game|accessdate=October 9, 2017|work=Bitmob|date=September 9, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330022351/http://bitmob.com/articles/oh-hai-bitmob-play-the-room-game|archivedate=March 30, 2012}}</ref> Infinite Lives,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frank|first1=Jenn|url=https://infinitelives.net/2010/09/08/the-room-the-video-game/|title=The Room, the video game|date=September 8, 2010|work=Infinite Lives|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Westword]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Klosowski|first1=Thorin|url=https://www.westword.com/arts/browser-pick-of-the-week-the-room-tribute-nsfw-5783186|title=Browser Pick of the Week: The Room Tribute (NSFW)|date=September 8, 2010|work=[[Westword]]|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> Game Culture,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gameculture.com/2010/09/07/room-point-and-click-8-bit-adventure-game|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100912145224/http://www.gameculture.com/2010/09/07/room-point-and-click-8-bit-adventure-game|archivedate=2010-09-12|title=The Room as a Point and Click, 8-Bit Adventure Game|date=September 9, 2010|work=Game Culture|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref> and Geeks of Doom.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dussault|first1=Jason|url=https://geeksofdoom.com/2010/09/09/must-play-tribute-flash-game-based-on-tommy-wiseaus-the-room/|title=Must Play: Tribute Flash Game Based On Tommy Wiseau\u2019s \u2018The Room\u2019|date=September 9, 2010|work=Geeks of Doom|accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn co-star [[Greg Sestero]]'s memoir, ''[[The Disaster Artist]]'', Sestero stated that during the filming of ''The Room'', he came up with the idea of having Mark be an undercover narcotics police officer to account for the disparate elements of his character, but the idea was rejected by Wiseau. Sestero \"had a good laugh\" when playing the game and seeing that its developers had given Mark a similar backstory by portraying him as a narcissistic [[hedonist]].<ref name=\"disaster\">''The Disaster Artist: My Life Inside the Room'' by [[Greg Sestero]] and [[Tom Bissell]], pg. 196. [[Simon & Schuster]], 2013.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.newgrounds.com/portal/view/547307}}\n*{{imdbtitle|7386506|The Room Tribute}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Room Tribute, The}}\n[[Category:2010 video games]]\n[[Category:Browser games]]\n[[Category:Fangames]]\n[[Category:Flash games]]\n[[Category:Role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Video games based on films]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 2003]]\n[[Category:Video games set in San Francisco]]\n", "name_user": "DemonDays64", "label": "safe", "comment": "Importing Wikidatashort description: \"2010 flash video game\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Room_Tribute"}
{"title_page": "Salesforce Tower", "text_new": "{{About|the building in San Francisco|the building in London|Heron Tower|the building in Indianapolis|Salesforce Tower (Indianapolis)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name            = Salesforce Tower\n| former_names    = Transbay Tower\n| image           = Salesforce Tower SF 2017.jpg\n| image_size      = 250px\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.salesforcetower.com/}}\n| caption         = Under construction in September 2017\n| location        = [[Mission Street|415 Mission Street]]<br/> [[San Francisco, California]]\n| coordinates     = {{coord|37.7899|-122.3969|region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map     = United States San Francisco Central#California#USA\n| map_caption     = Location in [[San Francisco]]##Location in [[California]]##Location in United States\n| pushpin_label   = Salesforce Tower\n| highest_region  = [[List of tallest buildings in California|San Francisco]]\n| highest_prev    = [[Transamerica Pyramid]]\n| highest_next    = \n| highest_start   = 2018\n| highest_end     = \n| completion_date = 2018\n| status          = Complete\n| start_date      = {{start date|2013}}\n| opening         = January 8, 2018\n| building_type   = Commercial offices, retail\n| height          = {{Convert|1,070|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"clarkconstruction.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clarkconstruction.com/our-work/projects/salesforce-tower|title=Salesforce Tower - Clark Construction|publisher=Clark Construction Group, LLC}}</ref>\n| top_floor       = \n| floor_count     = 61\n| elevator_count  = 34\n| cost            = US$1.1 billion\n| floor_area      = {{nowrap|{{convert|1600000|sqft|abbr=on}}}}\n| architect       = [[C\u00e9sar Pelli|Pelli Clarke Pelli Architects]]\n| engineer        = [[Magnusson Klemencic Associates]]\n| main_contractor = [[Clark Construction|Clark Construction Group]] /<br/>[[Hathaway Dinwiddie]] (joint venture)\n| developer       = [[Boston Properties]]\n| owner           = [[Boston Properties]] (100%)\n| management      = \n| references      = <ref name=\"sfplanning\">{{cite web |url=http://commissions.sfplanning.org/cpcpackets/2008.0789K%20&%202012.0257EBX.pdf |title=Project Description: 101 First Street (Transbay Tower) |publisher=San Francisco Planning Commission |date=2012-10-04 |accessdate=2013-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Emporis|307246}}</ref><ref>{{SkyscraperPage|41341}}</ref><ref>{{Structurae|20048908}}</ref><ref name=\"Pelli\">{{Cite web|title=Pelli Clarke Pelli Transbay Tower Description|url=http://pcparch.com/project/transbay-tower|accessdate=2014-03-21}}</ref><ref name=\"SFGATE3\">{{cite news|title=Plan B: Architects: Pelli Clarke Pelli|first=John|last=King|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/place/article/Plan-B-Architects-Pelli-Clarke-Pelli-2548233.php|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=2007-08-12|accessdate=2007-09-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Aggressive schedule' for proposed Transbay transit center, tower (picture)|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Aggressive-schedule-for-proposed-Transbay-2501939.php|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate=2008-02-17|date=2007-09-21 | first=John | last=King}}</ref><ref name=\"shrunk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.socketsite.com/archives/2012/03/san_franciscos_proposed_transbay_tower_has_shrunk.html |title=Yes, The Proposed Transbay Transit Tower Shrank A Hundred Feet |work=SocketSite |date=2012-03-12 |accessdate=2013-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"boston-salesforce-2014\">{{cite press release |url=http://news.theregistrysf.com/boston-properties-signs-714000-square-foot-lease-salesforce-com-salesforce-tower-formerly-transbay-tower/ |title=Boston Properties Signs a 714,000 Square Foot Lease with Salesforce.com at Salesforce Tower (Formerly Transbay Tower) |date=April 11, 2014 |publisher=The Registry}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Salesforce Tower''', formerly known as the '''Transbay Tower''', is a {{Convert|1,070|ft|m|0|adj=on}}<ref name=\"clarkconstruction.com\"/> office [[skyscraper]] in the [[South of Market, San Francisco|South of Market]] district of downtown [[San Francisco]]. It is located at [[Mission Street|415 Mission Street]] between First and Fremont Streets, next to the [[Transbay Transit Center]] site. Salesforce Tower is the centerpiece of the [[San Francisco Transbay development|San Francisco Transbay redevelopment plan]]. The plan contains a mix of office, transportation, retail, and residential uses. This was the last building designed by [[C\u00e9sar Pelli]] to be completed in his lifetime.\n\nUpon its completion in 2018 it became the tallest skyscraper in the San Francisco skyline, with a top roof height of {{convert|970|ft|m|0}} and overall height of {{convert|1070|ft|m|0}}, surpassing the {{convert|853|ft|m|0}} [[Transamerica Pyramid]]. It is also the second-tallest building west of the [[Mississippi River]] after the {{convert|1100|ft|m|0}} [[Wilshire Grand Center]] in Los Angeles. While the Salesforce Tower is taller than the Wilshire Grand if decorative spires are excluded,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cityminded.org/la-vs-sf-battle-tallest-building-12321|title=LA vs SF in Battle for Tallest Building|date=2015-01-26|access-date=2015-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ladowntownnews.com/news/an-amazing-view-of-the-wilshire-grand-spire/article_9e64fe84-76c5-11e6-8186-bb1b8b87c2f5.html |title=An Amazing View of the Wilshire Grand Spire |date=12 September 2016 |work=Los Angeles Downtown News |first=Nicholas |last=Slayton |access-date=13 September 2016}}</ref> the Salesforce Tower has a shorter roofline than Los Angeles' [[U.S. Bank Tower]], meaning that the Salesforce tower is also second-tallest according to roofline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctbuh.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=qH7LkIkhjQc%3D |title=Tall Buildings in Numbers: Tallest Helipads |work=CTBUH Journal, 2014 Issue II |publisher=The Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDeveloper [[Hines Interests Limited Partnership]], with a proposal by architect [[C\u00e9sar Pelli]] of Pelli Clarke Pelli Architects,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texasironandmetal.com/reach-new-heights-with-steel/|title=Buildings in the United States made with steel|work=Reach New Heights with Steel|accessdate=2019-07-12}}</ref> was selected as the winner of a global competition in 2007 to entitle and purchase the site. A seven-member jury of development experts assembled by the Transbay Joint Powers Authority (TJPA) selected Hines over proposals from Forest City Enterprises and architect Richard Rogers; and from Rockefeller Development Group Corp. and Skidmore Owings & Merrill.<ref name=\"king2007\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Jury-names-favorite-for-Transbay-terminal-tower-2504420.php |title=Jury names favorite for Transbay terminal, tower |first=John |last=King |date=2007-09-10 |accessdate=2014-03-21 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> In 2012, [[Boston Properties]] acquired a 50% stake in the project and in 2013 acquired most of Hines' remaining interest to become 95% owners of the project.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/blog/2013/03/change-at-transbay-tower-boston.html |title=Boston Properties takes control of Transbay Tower, S.F.'s tallest building |first=J.K. |last=Dineen |date=2013-03-19 |accessdate=2014-03-21}}</ref>\n\nThe site of the tower was in a dilapidated area, formerly used as a ground-level entrance to the [[San Francisco Transbay Terminal]], which was demolished in 2011. The TJPA sold the parcel to Boston Properties and Hines for US$192 million,<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20130326006392/en/Boston-Properties-Hines-Close-Record-Land-Sale |title=Boston Properties and Hines Close on Record Land Sale for Transbay Transit Tower Parcel |date=March 26, 2013 |publisher=BusinessWire}}</ref> and ceremonial groundbreaking for the new tower occurred on March 27, 2013, with below-grade construction work starting in late 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/blog/2013/03/hines-boston-properties-sling.html?page=all |title=Hines, Boston Properties sling ceremonial dirt in Transbay ground-breaking |last=Dineen |first=J.K. |work=San Francisco Business Times |date=2013-03-27 |accessdate=2013-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"clark2013\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.clarkconstruction.com/news/clark-build-san-franciscos-transbay-tower |title=Clark to Build San Francisco's Transbay Tower |date=2013-08-12 |accessdate=2014-03-21}}</ref>  The project is a joint venture between general contractors [[Clark Construction]] and [[Hathaway Dinwiddie Construction]].<ref name=\"clark2013\"/><ref name=nbc13>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/The-Man-Behind-the-New-Transbay-Tower-200351781.html |title=The Man Behind the New Transbay Tower |first=Joe |last=Rosato Jr. |work=NBC Bay Area |date=2013-03-28 |accessdate=2013-04-06}}</ref>\n\nThe development was originally contracted on spec, as Hines did not have a major tenant lease secured beforehand. On April 11, 2014, [[Salesforce.com]] announced that it signed a lease for {{convert|714,000|sqft}} to become the building's anchor tenant.<ref name=\"boston-salesforce-2014\"/> Previously known as the Transbay Tower, the building was renamed Salesforce Tower.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Salesforce-makes-landmark-deal-to-lease-half-of-5394954.php |title=Salesforce makes landmark deal to lease half of Transbay Tower |authors=Ellen Huet and John Cot\u00e9 |date=April 11, 2014 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> The lease was valued at US$560 million over 15 and a half years starting in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/blog/2014/04/salesforce-transbay-tower-san-francisco.html?page=all |title=Salesforce dominates Transbay Tower with San Francisco's biggest lease ever |first=Patrick |last=Hoge |work=San Francisco Business Times |date=April 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe tower opened in 2018 and has 61 floors, with a decorative crown reaching {{convert|1070|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}. The original proposal called for a {{convert|1200|ft|adj=on}} tower, but the height was later reduced.<ref name=\"shrunk\"/> The building's first tenants began moving in on January 8, 2018. Upon opening, the building was 97% leased to tenants including Salesforce, [[Covington & Burling]], [[WeWork]], [[Bain & Company]], [[Accenture]], [[McDermott Will & Emery]] and [[Hellman & Friedman]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2018/01/10/san-francisco-salesforce-crm-tower-opens-bostonbxp.html |title=San Francisco's tallest building, Salesforce Tower, opens at 97 percent leased |first=Blanca |last=Torres |date=January 10, 2018 |work=San Francisco Business Times}}</ref>\n\nThe 61st floor is known as the \"Ohana Floor\" and serves as an observation deck and lounge for Salesforce employees and guests. It is made available for use by nonprofits on evenings and weekends.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sf.curbed.com/2018/9/24/17897050/salesforce-tower-ohana-floor-top-floor-views-tallest |title=Here's the view from Salesforce Tower's Ohana Floor|first=Brock |last=Keeling |date=September 24, 2018 |work=Curbed San Francisco}}</ref> The Transbay Transit Center is located directly adjacent to the building, and is connected to the park level by a bridge on the 5th floor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2019/07/01/salesforce-transbay-transit-center-partially-reopens-without-bus-service/|title=San Francisco Transbay Transit Center Reopens Without Bus Service|work=CBS News San Francisco Bay Area|date=July 1, 2019|accessdate=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2019, the company announced and opened advance registration for public tours of the \"Ohana Floor\" once every month starting February 23.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.salesforcetowertours.com |title=Salesforce Tower Tours}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Boston Properties bought out Hines' remaining 5% stake in the building to become the sole owner and operator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://realassets.ipe.com/news/boston-properties-takes-full-control-of-salesforce-tower-as-hines-sells-out/10031075.fullarticle|title=Boston Properties takes full control of Salesforce Tower as Hines sells out|last=Peterson|first=Jon|date=9 May 2019|website=IPE RA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\nSalesforce Tower consists of a glass and steel curtain wall, surrounding a structural steel frame, which surrounds a reinforced concrete core. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.escsi.org/salesforce-tower/|title=ESCSI Salesforce Towerdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe footprint of Salesforce Tower rests on [[Land reclamation|land fill]] near San Francisco's original waterfront, an area prone to [[soil liquefaction]] during [[earthquake]]s. To account for this seismic risk, the tower uses a design that is modeled to withstand the strongest earthquakes expected in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theconcocompanies.weebly.com/blog/the-slalalalalalalalalalllalallalallalalalalalalalalalalesforce-tower-utilizes-a-performance-based-seismic-design|title=The Salesforce Tower Utilizes a \"Performance-based Seismic Design\"|publisher=Conco|date=December 20, 2015|accessdate=July 9, 2017}}</ref>  Its foundation includes 42 [[piling|piles]] driven down nearly {{convert|300|ft}} to [[bedrock]] and a {{convert|14|ft|adj=on}} thick [[foundation mat]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/2015/11/it-took-18-hours-to-pour-san-franciscos-biggest-ever-concrete-foundation/ |title=It Took 18 Hours to Pour the Foundation for San Francisco's Tallest Skyscraper |first=Nick |last=Stockton |date=November 11, 2015 |work=WIRED}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nOn 10 April 2019, the [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]] (CTBUH) named Salesforce Tower as the \u201cBest Tall Building Worldwide\" for 2019 at the 17th Annual CTBUH International Best Tall Building Awards Symposium, Ceremony & Dinner, celebrated at the Grand Hyatt Shenzhen, [[Shenzhen]], China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tallinnovation2019.com/2019-winners/|title=CTBUH Names 2019 Best Tall Building Worldwide, Among 20 Other Award Winners!|website=tallinnovation2019.com|date=April 10, 2019|access-date=May 29, 2019|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2019/04/12/ctbuh-awards-salesforce-tower-san-francisco/amp/|title=CTBUH names San Francisco's Salesforce Tower world's \"best tall building|website=www.dezeen.com|first=Bridget|last=Cogley|date=April 12, 2019|access-date=May 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n===Films & TV series===\n* Salesforce Tower's trash is you  first appearance in film was the 2014 animated film ''[[Big Hero 6 (film)|Big Hero 6]]''. Although Salesforce Tower was still under construction when the film was released, it appeared in the film as a completed tower.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/salesforce/status/532672945689460737|title=Salesforce on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|date=November 12, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/hinesglobal/videos/974959785880066/|title=Hines: In case you missed it...|publisher=Facebook|date=September 4, 2015|accessdate=June 28, 2017}}</ref>\n* The tower can also be seen in several shots in the 2018 film ''[[Venom (2018 film)|Venom]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/amp/Marvel-Venom-trailer-san-francisco-hardy-12860828.php|title=Here are the San Francisco locations we spotted in Marvel's new 'Venom' trailer|website=sfgate.com|first=Alyssa|last=Pereira|date=April 24, 2018|accessdate=July 29, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729184814/https://www.sfgate.com/movies/amp/Marvel-Venom-trailer-san-francisco-hardy-12860828.php|archivedate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n* In [[Ubisoft]]'s ''[[Watch Dogs 2]]'', the tower can also be seen completed, even though the video game was released in 2016 and set in that same year, while the building was still under construction.<ref>http://www.sfchronicle.com/entertainment/article/How-video-game-makers-build-a-better-SF-pixel-by-10814384.php</ref>\n\n===Others===\n* The crown of the tower features a nine-story electronic sculpture, \"Day for Night\", created by artist [[Jim Campbell (artist)|Jim Campbell]] that features low resolution, abstract videos of San Francisco that will be filmed each day. At its activation on May 21, 2018, it was considered the tallest public art piece in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/art/article/Preview-of-Salesforce-sculpture-at-Hosfelt-Gallery-12195446.php|title=Preview of Salesforce sculpture at Hosfelt Gallery|publisher=SF Gate|author=Whiting, Sam|date=September 13, 2017|accessdate=September 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-bright-lights-of-the-salesforce-tower|title=The Bright Lights of the Salesforce Tower|publisher=The New Yorker|author=Heller, Nathan|date=May 25, 2018|accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref>\n* For Halloween 2018, in response to a petition that gathered 11,000 signatures, the tower's pinnacle light installation was made to look like the [[Sauron|Eye of Sauron]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Eye-of-Sauron-San-Francisco-salesforce-tower-what-13353220.php|title=Fiery Eye of Sauron stares down San Francisco from atop Salesforce Tower - SFChronicle.com|date=2018-11-01|website=www.sfgate.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref>\n* Salesforce Tower is also included in the [[Lego Architecture]] 'San Francisco Skyline' set, released in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shop.lego.com/en-AU/product/San-Francisco-21043|title=San Francisco - 21043 {{!}} Architecture {{!}} LEGO Shop|website=shop.lego.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=180px>\nFile:Salesforce Tower April 2017.jpg|Salesforce Tower in April 2017, the day before its topping-out ceremony\nFile:SFO skyline 09 2017 6224 cropped.jpg|The Salesforce Tower (left) and the [[Transamerica Pyramid]] (right)</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|San Francisco Bay Area}}\n*[[List of tallest buildings in San Francisco]]\n*[[List of tallest buildings in California]]\n*[[List of tallest buildings in the United States]]\n*[[Gran Torre Santiago]]\n*[[Heron Tower]]\n*[[Salesforce Tower (Indianapolis)]]\n*[[Salesforce Tower (Sydney)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{official website}}\n*[http://www.transbayblog.com Transbay Demolition and Construction Blog]\n*[http://oxblue.com/open/clarkconstruction/salesforcetower Salesforce Tower construction webcam]\n*[http://pcparch.com/project/transbay-tower Transbay Transit Center proposal from Pelli Clarke Pelli Architects]\n\n{{Supertall skyscrapers | under-construction}}\n{{Buildings in San Francisco}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salesforce Tower}}\n[[Category:Salesforce.com]]\n[[Category:Economy of San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Hines Interests Limited Partnership]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:South of Market, San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Information technology company headquarters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 2018]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:C\u00e9sar Pelli buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the building in San Francisco|the building in London|Heron Tower|the building in Indianapolis|Salesforce Tower (Indianapolis)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name            = Salesforce Tower\n| former_names    = Transbay Tower\n| image           = Salesforce Tower SF 2017.jpg\n| image_size      = 250px\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.salesforcetower.com/}}\n| caption         = Under construction in September 2017\n| location        = [[Mission Street|415 Mission Street]]<br/> [[San Francisco, California]]\n| coordinates     = {{coord|37.7899|-122.3969|region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map     = United States San Francisco Central#California#USA\n| map_caption     = Location in [[San Francisco]]##Location in [[California]]##Location in United States\n| pushpin_label   = Salesforce Tower\n| highest_region  = [[List of tallest buildings in California|San Francisco]]\n| highest_prev    = [[Transamerica Pyramid]]\n| highest_next    = \n| highest_start   = 2018\n| highest_end     = \n| completion_date = 2018\n| status          = Complete\n| start_date      = {{start date|2013}}\n| opening         = January 8, 2018\n| building_type   = Commercial offices, retail\n| height          = {{Convert|1,070|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"clarkconstruction.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clarkconstruction.com/our-work/projects/salesforce-tower|title=Salesforce Tower - Clark Construction|publisher=Clark Construction Group, LLC}}</ref>\n| top_floor       = \n| floor_count     = 61\n| elevator_count  = 34\n| cost            = US$1.1 billion\n| floor_area      = {{nowrap|{{convert|1600000|sqft|abbr=on}}}}\n| architect       = [[C\u00e9sar Pelli|Pelli Clarke Pelli Architects]]\n| engineer        = [[Magnusson Klemencic Associates]]\n| main_contractor = [[Clark Construction|Clark Construction Group]] /<br/>[[Hathaway Dinwiddie]] (joint venture)\n| developer       = [[Boston Properties]]\n| owner           = [[Boston Properties]] (100%)\n| management      = \n| references      = <ref name=\"sfplanning\">{{cite web |url=http://commissions.sfplanning.org/cpcpackets/2008.0789K%20&%202012.0257EBX.pdf |title=Project Description: 101 First Street (Transbay Tower) |publisher=San Francisco Planning Commission |date=2012-10-04 |accessdate=2013-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Emporis|307246}}</ref><ref>{{SkyscraperPage|41341}}</ref><ref>{{Structurae|20048908}}</ref><ref name=\"Pelli\">{{Cite web|title=Pelli Clarke Pelli Transbay Tower Description|url=http://pcparch.com/project/transbay-tower|accessdate=2014-03-21}}</ref><ref name=\"SFGATE3\">{{cite news|title=Plan B: Architects: Pelli Clarke Pelli|first=John|last=King|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/place/article/Plan-B-Architects-Pelli-Clarke-Pelli-2548233.php|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=2007-08-12|accessdate=2007-09-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Aggressive schedule' for proposed Transbay transit center, tower (picture)|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Aggressive-schedule-for-proposed-Transbay-2501939.php|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate=2008-02-17|date=2007-09-21 | first=John | last=King}}</ref><ref name=\"shrunk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.socketsite.com/archives/2012/03/san_franciscos_proposed_transbay_tower_has_shrunk.html |title=Yes, The Proposed Transbay Transit Tower Shrank A Hundred Feet |work=SocketSite |date=2012-03-12 |accessdate=2013-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"boston-salesforce-2014\">{{cite press release |url=http://news.theregistrysf.com/boston-properties-signs-714000-square-foot-lease-salesforce-com-salesforce-tower-formerly-transbay-tower/ |title=Boston Properties Signs a 714,000 Square Foot Lease with Salesforce.com at Salesforce Tower (Formerly Transbay Tower) |date=April 11, 2014 |publisher=The Registry}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Salesforce Tower''', formerly known as the '''Transbay Tower''', is a {{Convert|1,070|ft|m|0|adj=on}}<ref name=\"clarkconstruction.com\"/> office [[skyscraper]] in the [[South of Market, San Francisco|South of Market]] district of downtown [[San Francisco]]. It is located at [[Mission Street|415 Mission Street]] between First and Fremont Streets, next to the [[Transbay Transit Center]] site. Salesforce Tower is the centerpiece of the [[San Francisco Transbay development|San Francisco Transbay redevelopment plan]]. The plan contains a mix of office, transportation, retail, and residential uses. This was the last building designed by [[C\u00e9sar Pelli]] to be completed in his lifetime.\n\nUpon its completion in 2018 it became the tallest skyscraper in the San Francisco skyline, with a top roof height of {{convert|970|ft|m|0}} and overall height of {{convert|1070|ft|m|0}}, surpassing the {{convert|853|ft|m|0}} [[Transamerica Pyramid]]. It is also the second-tallest building west of the [[Mississippi River]] after the {{convert|1100|ft|m|0}} [[Wilshire Grand Center]] in Los Angeles. While the Salesforce Tower is taller than the Wilshire Grand if decorative spires are excluded,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cityminded.org/la-vs-sf-battle-tallest-building-12321|title=LA vs SF in Battle for Tallest Building|date=2015-01-26|access-date=2015-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ladowntownnews.com/news/an-amazing-view-of-the-wilshire-grand-spire/article_9e64fe84-76c5-11e6-8186-bb1b8b87c2f5.html |title=An Amazing View of the Wilshire Grand Spire |date=12 September 2016 |work=Los Angeles Downtown News |first=Nicholas |last=Slayton |access-date=13 September 2016}}</ref> the Salesforce Tower has a shorter roofline than Los Angeles' [[U.S. Bank Tower]], meaning that the Salesforce tower is also second-tallest according to roofline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctbuh.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=qH7LkIkhjQc%3D |title=Tall Buildings in Numbers: Tallest Helipads |work=CTBUH Journal, 2014 Issue II |publisher=The Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDeveloper [[Hines Interests Limited Partnership]], with a proposal by architect [[C\u00e9sar Pelli]] of Pelli Clarke Pelli Architects,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texasironandmetal.com/reach-new-heights-with-steel/|title=Buildings in the United States made with steel|work=Reach New Heights with Steel|accessdate=2019-07-12}}</ref> was selected as the winner of a global competition in 2007 to entitle and purchase the site. A seven-member jury of development experts assembled by the Transbay Joint Powers Authority (TJPA) selected Hines over proposals from Forest City Enterprises and architect Richard Rogers; and from Rockefeller Development Group Corp. and Skidmore Owings & Merrill.<ref name=\"king2007\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Jury-names-favorite-for-Transbay-terminal-tower-2504420.php |title=Jury names favorite for Transbay terminal, tower |first=John |last=King |date=2007-09-10 |accessdate=2014-03-21 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> In 2012, [[Boston Properties]] acquired a 50% stake in the project and in 2013 acquired most of Hines' remaining interest to become 95% owners of the project.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/blog/2013/03/change-at-transbay-tower-boston.html |title=Boston Properties takes control of Transbay Tower, S.F.'s tallest building |first=J.K. |last=Dineen |date=2013-03-19 |accessdate=2014-03-21}}</ref>\n\nThe site of the tower was in a dilapidated area, formerly used as a ground-level entrance to the [[San Francisco Transbay Terminal]], which was demolished in 2011. The TJPA sold the parcel to Boston Properties and Hines for US$192 million,<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20130326006392/en/Boston-Properties-Hines-Close-Record-Land-Sale |title=Boston Properties and Hines Close on Record Land Sale for Transbay Transit Tower Parcel |date=March 26, 2013 |publisher=BusinessWire}}</ref> and ceremonial groundbreaking for the new tower occurred on March 27, 2013, with below-grade construction work starting in late 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/blog/2013/03/hines-boston-properties-sling.html?page=all |title=Hines, Boston Properties sling ceremonial dirt in Transbay ground-breaking |last=Dineen |first=J.K. |work=San Francisco Business Times |date=2013-03-27 |accessdate=2013-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"clark2013\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.clarkconstruction.com/news/clark-build-san-franciscos-transbay-tower |title=Clark to Build San Francisco's Transbay Tower |date=2013-08-12 |accessdate=2014-03-21}}</ref>  The project is a joint venture between general contractors [[Clark Construction]] and [[Hathaway Dinwiddie Construction]].<ref name=\"clark2013\"/><ref name=nbc13>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/The-Man-Behind-the-New-Transbay-Tower-200351781.html |title=The Man Behind the New Transbay Tower |first=Joe |last=Rosato Jr. |work=NBC Bay Area |date=2013-03-28 |accessdate=2013-04-06}}</ref>\n\nThe development was originally contracted on spec, as Hines did not have a major tenant lease secured beforehand. On April 11, 2014, [[Salesforce.com]] announced that it signed a lease for {{convert|714,000|sqft}} to become the building's anchor tenant.<ref name=\"boston-salesforce-2014\"/> Previously known as the Transbay Tower, the building was renamed Salesforce Tower.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Salesforce-makes-landmark-deal-to-lease-half-of-5394954.php |title=Salesforce makes landmark deal to lease half of Transbay Tower |authors=Ellen Huet and John Cot\u00e9 |date=April 11, 2014 |work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> The lease was valued at US$560 million over 15 and a half years starting in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/blog/2014/04/salesforce-transbay-tower-san-francisco.html?page=all |title=Salesforce dominates Transbay Tower with San Francisco's biggest lease ever |first=Patrick |last=Hoge |work=San Francisco Business Times |date=April 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe tower opened in 2018 and has 61 floors, with a decorative crown reaching {{convert|1070|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}. The original proposal called for a {{convert|1200|ft|adj=on}} tower, but the height was later reduced.<ref name=\"shrunk\"/> The building's first tenants began moving in on January 8, 2018. Upon opening, the building was 97% leased to tenants including Salesforce, [[Covington & Burling]], [[WeWork]], [[Bain & Company]], [[Accenture]], [[McDermott Will & Emery]] and [[Hellman & Friedman]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2018/01/10/san-francisco-salesforce-crm-tower-opens-bostonbxp.html |title=San Francisco's tallest building, Salesforce Tower, opens at 97 percent leased |first=Blanca |last=Torres |date=January 10, 2018 |work=San Francisco Business Times}}</ref>\n\nThe 61st floor is known as the \"Ohana Floor\" and serves as an observation deck and lounge for Salesforce employees and guests. It is made available for use by nonprofits on evenings and weekends.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sf.curbed.com/2018/9/24/17897050/salesforce-tower-ohana-floor-top-floor-views-tallest |title=Here's the view from Salesforce Tower's Ohana Floor|first=Brock |last=Keeling |date=September 24, 2018 |work=Curbed San Francisco}}</ref> The Transbay Transit Center is located directly adjacent to the building, and is connected to the park level by a bridge on the 5th floor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2019/07/01/salesforce-transbay-transit-center-partially-reopens-without-bus-service/|title=San Francisco Transbay Transit Center Reopens Without Bus Service|work=CBS News San Francisco Bay Area|date=July 1, 2019|accessdate=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2019, the company announced and opened advance registration for public tours of the \"Ohana Floor\" once every month starting February 23.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.salesforcetowertours.com |title=Salesforce Tower Tours}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Boston Properties bought out Hines' remaining 5% stake in the building to become the sole owner and operator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://realassets.ipe.com/news/boston-properties-takes-full-control-of-salesforce-tower-as-hines-sells-out/10031075.fullarticle|title=Boston Properties takes full control of Salesforce Tower as Hines sells out|last=Peterson|first=Jon|date=9 May 2019|website=IPE RA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\nSalesforce Tower consists of a glass and steel curtain wall, surrounding a structural steel frame, which surrounds a reinforced concrete core. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.escsi.org/salesforce-tower/|title=ESCSI Salesforce Towerdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe footprint of Salesforce Tower rests on [[Land reclamation|land fill]] near San Francisco's original waterfront, an area prone to [[soil liquefaction]] during [[earthquake]]s. To account for this seismic risk, the tower uses a design that is modeled to withstand the strongest earthquakes expected in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theconcocompanies.weebly.com/blog/the-salesforce-tower-utilizes-a-performance-based-seismic-design|title=The Salesforce Tower Utilizes a \"Performance-based Seismic Design\"|publisher=Conco|date=December 20, 2015|accessdate=July 9, 2017}}</ref>  Its foundation includes 42 [[piling|piles]] driven down nearly {{convert|300|ft}} to [[bedrock]] and a {{convert|14|ft|adj=on}} thick [[foundation mat]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/2015/11/it-took-18-hours-to-pour-san-franciscos-biggest-ever-concrete-foundation/ |title=It Took 18 Hours to Pour the Foundation for San Francisco's Tallest Skyscraper |first=Nick |last=Stockton |date=November 11, 2015 |work=WIRED}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nOn 10 April 2019, the [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]] (CTBUH) named Salesforce Tower as the \u201cBest Tall Building Worldwide\" for 2019 at the 17th Annual CTBUH International Best Tall Building Awards Symposium, Ceremony & Dinner, celebrated at the Grand Hyatt Shenzhen, [[Shenzhen]], China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tallinnovation2019.com/2019-winners/|title=CTBUH Names 2019 Best Tall Building Worldwide, Among 20 Other Award Winners!|website=tallinnovation2019.com|date=April 10, 2019|access-date=May 29, 2019|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2019/04/12/ctbuh-awards-salesforce-tower-san-francisco/amp/|title=CTBUH names San Francisco's Salesforce Tower world's \"best tall building|website=www.dezeen.com|first=Bridget|last=Cogley|date=April 12, 2019|access-date=May 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n===Films & TV series===\n* Salesforce Tower's first appearance in film was the 2014 animated film ''[[Big Hero 6 (film)|Big Hero 6]]''. Although Salesforce Tower was still under construction when the film was released, it appeared in the film as a completed tower.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/salesforce/status/532672945689460737|title=Salesforce on Twitter|publisher=Twitter|date=November 12, 2014|accessdate=June 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/hinesglobal/videos/974959785880066/|title=Hines: In case you missed it...|publisher=Facebook|date=September 4, 2015|accessdate=June 28, 2017}}</ref>\n* The tower can also be seen in several shots in the 2018 film ''[[Venom (2018 film)|Venom]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/amp/Marvel-Venom-trailer-san-francisco-hardy-12860828.php|title=Here are the San Francisco locations we spotted in Marvel's new 'Venom' trailer|website=sfgate.com|first=Alyssa|last=Pereira|date=April 24, 2018|accessdate=July 29, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729184814/https://www.sfgate.com/movies/amp/Marvel-Venom-trailer-san-francisco-hardy-12860828.php|archivedate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n* In [[Ubisoft]]'s ''[[Watch Dogs 2]]'', the tower can also be seen completed, even though the video game was released in 2016 and set in that same year, while the building was still under construction.<ref>http://www.sfchronicle.com/entertainment/article/How-video-game-makers-build-a-better-SF-pixel-by-10814384.php</ref>\n\n===Others===\n* The crown of the tower features a nine-story electronic sculpture, \"Day for Night\", created by artist [[Jim Campbell (artist)|Jim Campbell]] that features low resolution, abstract videos of San Francisco that will be filmed each day. At its activation on May 21, 2018, it was considered the tallest public art piece in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/art/article/Preview-of-Salesforce-sculpture-at-Hosfelt-Gallery-12195446.php|title=Preview of Salesforce sculpture at Hosfelt Gallery|publisher=SF Gate|author=Whiting, Sam|date=September 13, 2017|accessdate=September 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/the-bright-lights-of-the-salesforce-tower|title=The Bright Lights of the Salesforce Tower|publisher=The New Yorker|author=Heller, Nathan|date=May 25, 2018|accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref>\n* For Halloween 2018, in response to a petition that gathered 11,000 signatures, the tower's pinnacle light installation was made to look like the [[Sauron|Eye of Sauron]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Eye-of-Sauron-San-Francisco-salesforce-tower-what-13353220.php|title=Fiery Eye of Sauron stares down San Francisco from atop Salesforce Tower - SFChronicle.com|date=2018-11-01|website=www.sfgate.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref>\n* Salesforce Tower is also included in the [[Lego Architecture]] 'San Francisco Skyline' set, released in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shop.lego.com/en-AU/product/San-Francisco-21043|title=San Francisco - 21043 {{!}} Architecture {{!}} LEGO Shop|website=shop.lego.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=180px>\nFile:Salesforce Tower April 2017.jpg|Salesforce Tower in April 2017, the day before its topping-out ceremony\nFile:SFO skyline 09 2017 6224 cropped.jpg|The Salesforce Tower (left) and the [[Transamerica Pyramid]] (right)</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|San Francisco Bay Area}}\n*[[List of tallest buildings in San Francisco]]\n*[[List of tallest buildings in California]]\n*[[List of tallest buildings in the United States]]\n*[[Gran Torre Santiago]]\n*[[Heron Tower]]\n*[[Salesforce Tower (Indianapolis)]]\n*[[Salesforce Tower (Sydney)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{