{"title_page": "Seletar Camp", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name        = Seletar Camp\n| org/group   = \n| logo        = \n| logo_size   = \n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| alt         =\n| caption     = \n| coordinates = \n| location    = Jalan Kayu in [[Singapore]]\n| region      =\n| state       = \n| country     = \n| affiliation = \n| patron      = \n| network     = \n| standards   = \n| emergency   = \n| beds        = \n| speciality  = \n| helipad     = \n| founded     = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1928}}\n| closed      = \n| demolished  = \n| website     = \n| other_links = \n| module      = \n}}\n'''Seletar Camp''' is a military installation used by the [[Singapore Army]]. It is located at the northern tip of Singapore, by the [[Tampines Expressway]] and adjacent to [[Punggol Reservoir]]. The main route to the camp is Seletar Aerospace Way.\n\nSeletar Camp once houses many [[Singapore Combat Engineers|combat engineer]] units. It was the home of the [[Goh Keng Swee Command and Staff College|Command and Staff College]] from 1982 to 1995,<ref>{{cite web | publisher = Ministry of Defence, Singapore | title = Goh Keng Swee Command and Staff College: History | url = http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/mindef_websites/atozlistings/saftimi/units/GKSCSC/aboutus/History.html | date = 2011-09-20}}</ref> before moving to its permanent location at [[SAFTI Military Institute]]. It is opposite to the newly built [[Seletar Airport]]. It now houses [[Singapore Combat Engineers#Headquarters Army Combat Engineers Group (HQ ARMCEG)|HQ Army Combat Engineers Group]] (HQ ARMCEG).\n\n==History==\nSeletar Camp was built for the [[Royal Air Force]], and it became operational in 1928. It was controlled by the Japanese during [[Japanese occupation of Singapore]] in 1942 as one of the seven Indian Army personnel interned [[POW camp]]s, after the war in 1945, it was controlled by the British [[East of Suez|until 1971]].<ref name = zakaria>{{cite web | work = Singapore Infopedia | publisher = National Library Board | author = F. Zakaria | date = 2011-02-14 | url = http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1771_2011-02-28.html | title = Seletar Camp | access-date = 2012-02-05 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131017004950/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1771_2011-02-28.html | archive-date = 2013-10-17 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n[[RAF Seletar]] was also on the premises of Seletar Camp. It was used by the [[Republic of Singapore Air Force]] after the British withdrawal as Seletar Airbase, and it is now a general aviation civil airport known as [[Seletar Airport]]. It is adjacent to the current Seletar Camp. Parts of the Seletar Camp were converted to normal and ordinary use, with the building being shrunk in size.\n\nSeletar Camp formerly included hundreds of houses that served as quarters for RAF personnel. Many of the houses have been retained. The 160 Anti- Aircraft Gunners will also on  Seletar Camp but shifted its operations to Chong Pang Camp in 2002. Popularly known as \"black and whites\" they are owned by the [[government of Singapore]] and are available for lease. A small golf course and the [[Seletar Aerospace Park]] are on the former grounds of Seletar Camp.\n\nTo free up land for the redevelopment, the Army Combat Engineers Group and the sub-units were consolidated into a 30-hectare site, and the main gate was shifted to St. Martin Lane. In June 2012, DSTA completed the development of the site, and achieved significant intensification through meticulous planning. The result was the consolidation of administrative, training, maintenance and recreational facilities, as well as the accommodation which was originally housed in the low-rise buildings. To minimise the number of buildings, facilities with strong functional relationships and compatible building functions were housed together, 170 old buildings together with the old Medical Centre, were consolidated into 25 new multi-storey facilities, and these were spread along the original eastern camp of Seletar. The camp at present has been reduced to 30 hectares.\n\nOn 4 April 2019,  [[Singapore Combat Engineers#39th Battalion, Singapore Combat Engineers (39SCE)|39th Battalion Singapore Combat Engineers]] (39SCE), [[Singapore Combat Engineers#36th Battalion, Singapore Combat Engineers (36SCE)|36th Battalion Singapore Combat Engineers]] (36SCE) , CBRE Engineers Training  Centre (CETC) & [[Chemical, Biological, Radiological and Explosive Defence Group|HQ Chemical, Biological, Radiological and Explosive Defence Group]] (CBRE DG) has already closed down its operations in Seletar and shifted all its operations to Nee Soon Camp (includes the canteen and cookhouse that are inside the camp). This frees up space for additional developments in Seletar.\n\nToday only [[Singapore Combat Engineers#Headquarters Army Combat Engineers Group (HQ ARMCEG)|HQ Army Combat Engineers Group]] (HQ ARMCEG) stands at the other side of the camp.\n\n==References==\n<References/>\n\n{{coord missing|Singapore}}\n\n[[Category:Singapore Army]]\n[[Category:Military installations of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Military installations established in 1928]]\n[[Category:1928 establishments in Singapore]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoner of war camps in Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name        = Seletar Camp\n| org/group   = \n| logo        = \n| logo_size   = \n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| alt         =\n| caption     = \n| coordinates = \n| location    = Jalan Kayu in [[Singapore]]\n| region      =\n| state       = \n| country     = \n| affiliation = \n| patron      = \n| network     = \n| standards   = \n| emergency   = \n| beds        = \n| speciality  = \n| helipad     = \n| founded     = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1928}}\n| closed      = \n| demolished  = \n| website     = \n| other_links = \n| module      = \n}}\n'''Seletar Camp''' is a military installation used by the [[Singapore Army]]. It is located at the northern tip of Singapore, by the [[Tampines Expressway]] and adjacent to [[Punggol Reservoir]]. The main route to the camp is Seletar Aerospace Way.\n\nSeletar Camp once houses many [[Singapore Combat Engineers|combat engineer]] units. It was the home of the [[Goh Keng Swee Command and Staff College|Command and Staff College]] from 1982 to 1995,<ref>{{cite web | publisher = Ministry of Defence, Singapore | title = Goh Keng Swee Command and Staff College: History | url = http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/mindef_websites/atozlistings/saftimi/units/GKSCSC/aboutus/History.html | date = 2011-09-20}}</ref> before moving to its permanent location at [[SAFTI Military Institute]]. It is opposite to the newly built [[Seletar Airport]]. It now houses [[Singapore Combat Engineers#Headquarters Army Combat Engineers Group (HQ ARMCEG)|HQ Army Combat Engineers Group]] (HQ ARMCEG).\n\n==History==\nSeletar Camp was built for the [[Royal Air Force]], and it became operational in 1928. It was controlled by the Japanese during [[Japanese occupation of Singapore]] in 1942 as one of the seven Indian Army personnel interned [[POW camp]]s, after the war in 1945, it was controlled by the British [[East of Suez|until 1971]].<ref name = zakaria>{{cite web | work = Singapore Infopedia | publisher = National Library Board | author = F. Zakaria | date = 2011-02-14 | url = http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1771_2011-02-28.html | title = Seletar Camp | access-date = 2012-02-05 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131017004950/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1771_2011-02-28.html | archive-date = 2013-10-17 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n[[RAF Seletar]] was also on the premises of Seletar Camp. It was used by the [[Republic of Singapore Air Force]] after the British withdrawal as Seletar Airbase, and it is now a general aviation civil airport known as [[Seletar Airport]]. It is adjacent to the current Seletar Camp. Parts of the Seletar Camp were converted to normal and ordinary use, with the building being shrunk in size.\n\nSeletar Camp formerly included hundreds of houses that served as quarters for RAF personnel. Many of the houses have been retained. The 160 Anti- Aircraft Gunners will also on  Seletar Camp but shifted it's operations to Chong Pang Camp in 2002. Popularly known as \"black and whites\" they are owned by the [[government of Singapore]], and are available for lease. A small golf course and the [[Seletar Aerospace Park]] are on the former grounds of Seletar Camp.\n\nTo free up land for the redevelopment, the Army Combat Engineers Group and the sub-units were consolidated into a 30-hectare site, and the main gate was shifted to St. Martin Lane. In June 2012, DSTA completed the development of the site, and achieved significant intensification through meticulous planning. The result was the consolidation of administrative, training, maintenance and recreational facilities, as well as the accommodation which was originally housed in the low-rise buildings. To minimise the number of buildings, facilities with strong functional relationships and compatible building functions were housed together, 170 old buildings together with the old Medical Centre, were consolidated into 25 new multi-storey facilities, and these were spread along the original eastern camp of Seletar. The camp at present has been reduced to 30 hectares.\n\nOn 4 April 2019,  [[Singapore Combat Engineers#39th Battalion, Singapore Combat Engineers (39SCE)|39th Battalion Singapore Combat Engineers]] (39SCE), [[Singapore Combat Engineers#36th Battalion, Singapore Combat Engineers (36SCE)|36th Battalion Singapore Combat Engineers]] (36SCE) , CBRE Engineers Training  Centre (CETC) & [[Chemical, Biological, Radiological and Explosive Defence Group|HQ Chemical, Biological, Radiological and Explosive Defence Group]] (CBRE DG) has already closed down its operations in Seletar and shifted all its operations to Nee Soon Camp (includes the canteen & cookhouse that are inside the camp). This frees up the space for additional developments in Seletar.\n\nToday only [[Singapore Combat Engineers#Headquarters Army Combat Engineers Group (HQ ARMCEG)|HQ Army Combat Engineers Group]] (HQ ARMCEG) stands at the other side of the camp.\n\n==References==\n<References/>\n\n{{coord missing|Singapore}}\n\n[[Category:Singapore Army]]\n[[Category:Military installations of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Military installations established in 1928]]\n[[Category:1928 establishments in Singapore]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoner of war camps in Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "it's \u2192 its", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seletar_Camp"}
{"title_page": "\u221e-topos", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2017}}\n{{technical|date=May 2017}}\n}}\n\nIn [[mathematics]], an '''\u221e-topos''' is, roughly, an [[\u221e-category]] such that its objects behave like [[sheaf (mathematics)|sheaves]] of spaces with some choice of [[Grothendieck topology]]; in other words, it gives an intrinsic notion of sheaves without reference to an external space.<!--The notion is due to [[Alexander Grothendieck]], who considered ''n''-topos.--> The prototypical example of an \u221e-topos is the \u221e-category of sheaves of spaces on some topological space. But the notion is more flexible; for example, the \u221e-category of \u00e9tale sheaves on some [[Scheme (mathematics)|scheme]] is not the \u221e-category of sheaves on any topological space but it is still an \u221e-topos.\n\nPrecisely, in Lurie's ''[[Higher Topos Theory]]'', an \u221e-topos is defined<ref>{{harvnb|Lurie|2009|loc=Definition 6.1.0.4.}}</ref> as an \u221e-category ''X'' such that there is a small \u221e-category ''C'' and a left exact localization functor from the \u221e-category of [[presheaf of spaces|presheaves of spaces]] on ''C'' to ''X''. A theorem of Lurie<ref>{{harvnb|Lurie|2009|loc=Theorem 6.1.0.6.}}</ref> states that an \u221e-category is an \u221e-topos if and only if it satisfies an \u221e-categorical version of Giraud\u2019s axioms in ordinary topos theory. A \"[[topos]]\" is a category behaving like the category of sheaves of sets on a topological space. In analogy, Lurie's definition and characterization theorem of an \u221e-topos says that an \u221e-topos is an \u221e-category behaving like the category of sheaves of spaces.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Mathematics}}\n*[[Homotopy hypothesis]]\n*[[\u221e-groupoid]]\n*[[Simplicial set]]\n*[[Kan complex]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20200425203513/https://faculty.math.illinois.edu/~rezk/sag-chapter.pdf Spectral Algebraic Geometry] - Charles Rezk (gives a down-enough-to-earth introduction)\n*{{cite book |last1=Lurie |first1=Jacob |year=2009 |title=Higher Topos Theory |url=https://www.math.ias.edu/~lurie/papers/HTT.pdf |publisher=Princeton University Press |arxiv=math/0608040 |isbn=978-0-691-14049-0 }}\n\n{{Category theory}}\n\n[[Category:Higher category theory]]\n[[Category:Sheaf theory]]\n[[Category:Topos theory]]\n\n\n{{geometry-stub}}\n{{categorytheory-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2017}}\n{{technical|date=May 2017}}\n}}\n\nIn [[mathematics]], an '''\u221e-topos''' is, roughly, an [[\u221e-category]] such that its objects behave like [[sheaf (mathematics)|sheaves]] of spaces with some choice of [[Grothendieck topology]]; in other words, it gives an intrinsic notion of sheaves without reference to an external space.<!--The notion is due to [[Alexander Grothendieck]], who considered ''n''-topos.--> The prototypical example of an \u221e-topos is the \u221e-category of sheaves of spaces on some topological space. But the notion is more flexible; for example, the \u221e-category of \u00e9tale sheaves on some [[Scheme (mathematics)|scheme]] is not the \u221e-category of sheaves on any topological space but it is still an \u221e-topos.\n\nPrecisely, in Lurie's ''[[Higher Topos Theory]]'', an \u221e-topos is defined<ref>{{harvnb|Lurie|2009|loc=Definition 6.1.0.4.}}</ref> as an \u221e-category ''X'' such that there is a small \u221e-category ''C'' and a left exact localization functor from the \u221e-category of [[presheaf of spaces|presheaves of spaces]] on ''C'' to ''X''. A theorem of Lurie<ref>{{harvnb|Lurie|2009|loc=Theorem 6.1.0.6.}}</ref> states that an \u221e-category is an \u221e-topos if and only if it satisfies an \u221e-categorical version of Giraud\u2019s axioms in ordinary topos theory. A \"[[topos]]\" is a category behaving like the category of sheaves of sets on a topological space. In analogy, Lurie's definition and characterization theorem of an \u221e-topos says that an \u221e-topos is an \u221e-category behaving like the category of sheaves of spaces.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Mathematics}}\n*[[Homotopy hypothesis]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Lurie |first1=Jacob |year=2009 |title=Higher Topos Theory |url=https://www.math.ias.edu/~lurie/papers/HTT.pdf |publisher=Princeton University Press |arxiv=math/0608040 |isbn=978-0-691-14049-0 }}\n\n{{Category theory}}\n\n[[Category:Higher category theory]]\n[[Category:Sheaf theory]]\n[[Category:Topos theory]]\n\n\n{{geometry-stub}}\n{{categorytheory-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wundzer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E2%88%9E-topos"}
